column1: This is the basis of file 200_Prescriptions_2011.smi (folder "test").
It is based on a Wikipedia WikiProject, compiling the 200 top
prescriptions 2011 in the U.S.A, listed on the following address:
This listing was chosen because each of the entries already was
crosslinked to a corresponding entry in the English Wikipedia.
The sales figures in the original list were removed, but the
consecution of the entries is the same as in the source consulted.
Instead, SMILES strings of the principal active ingredient(s) is /
are now in the first column of each of the three tables here, a /
the name of the commercial drug name and the manufacturer follow
Table 1/3 thus is almost a copy of the original sources consulted.
Table 2/3 now only considers drugs of "small molecules" -- without
drugs e.g., derived from insuline, or antibodies.  If Wikipedia
stated more than one principal active ingredient, then this second
table lists the SMILES strings individually with the names of the
Table 3/3 reports only the relevant SMILES strings and drug names.
The file uses UTF-8 character encoding and separates columns by a
semi-colon.  New lines are indicated in the Windows format, e.g.

column1: Only "small molecule drugs" -- retaining the same consecution of entries as in
the original list (i.e, TABLE 1/3).  In presence of more than one active ingredient
the entry is split (e.g., Combivent_1, Combivent_2).
Only SMILES string and the (potentially enumerated) name of the drug are retained.
